=== EXPERT REVIEW HIGH/MEDIUM ===
25:That said, four correctness gaps need attention. Three are HIGH severity. First, the encryption posture in the Prerequisites table partially specifies per-data-class CMKs ("S3: SSE-KMS with customer-managed CMKs split by data class (PHI buckets get one CMK, operational/no-PHI buckets get another, model artifacts get a third)") but the breakdown is insufficient for the data classes this recipe actually creates: HealthLake datastore, raw ADT feeds, OR-schedule feeds, transfer-queue feeds, ED-board feeds, harmonized state snapshots, per-patient feature vectors, inflow samples, outflow samples, forecast outputs, Monte Carlo trajectory archives, model artifacts (three separate models), DynamoDB serving table, Bedrock prompt logs (if narrative summaries are enabled), and CloudWatch logs. Second, the Step Functions inference pipeline (state snapshot -> inflow models -> outflow model -> unit assignment -> Monte Carlo -> DynamoDB write) does not specify retry policy, dead-letter routing, partial-failure semantics, or stale-forecast signaling for missed cycles; for a pipeline whose missed cycles produce stale bed-huddle dashboards and stale transfer-center decisions at 30-minute granularity, this is the chapter-pattern failure mode that 12.2, 12.3, and 12.4 also surfaced. Third, the unit-assignment classifier and the overflow logic produce silent miscalibration in two ways that the recipe correctly diagnoses in prose but does not architecturally specify: hospital-specific overflow rules live in a configuration that the bed-management team owns and updates, and the recipe does not specify the configuration store, the change-management workflow, or the audit trail; service-line and DRG drift detection is correctly elevated in production-gaps but not architecturally specified.
27:Nine MEDIUM findings cluster on architectural specificity (CloudTrail data events not specified on PHI-bearing buckets, tables, and the HealthLake datastore; DynamoDB write idempotency and conditional-write semantics implicit; drift detection on inflow-model accuracy and outflow-model calibration architecturally implicit; ADT timestamp reconciliation pipeline implicit despite explicit prose elevation; feedback capture and continuous calibration loop architecturally implicit; discharge-order-timing model architecturally implicit despite "single biggest improvement" framing in production gaps; multi-hospital health-system rollout pattern architecturally implicit; Bedrock narrative-summary prompt-construction PHI handling architecturally implicit; VPC endpoint enumeration incomplete and endpoint-type not distinguished).
33:Priority breakdown: 0 CRITICAL, 3 HIGH, 9 MEDIUM, 8 LOW. **Verdict: PASS** because there are 0 CRITICAL findings and HIGH count (3) is at, but not above, the > 3 = FAIL threshold.
44:- **Encryption coverage spans the full data path.** The recipe is the first in chapter 12 to explicitly call out CMK splitting by data class in the Prerequisites table ("PHI buckets get one CMK, operational/no-PHI buckets get another, model artifacts get a third"), which is the chapter-pattern improvement that 12.2 and 12.3 needed and that 12.4's expert review elevated as Finding H1. The split is not yet granular enough for this recipe's full data-class inventory (see Finding S1) but the framing is correct.
46:- **CloudTrail enabled with the right framing.** "Enabled at the account level. Data events on PHI-bearing buckets, the HealthLake datastore, the DynamoDB serving table, and the customer-managed CMKs. Management events for SageMaker, Glue, Step Functions, EventBridge, DynamoDB, Lambda, and Bedrock. CloudTrail logs in a dedicated S3 bucket with Object Lock in compliance mode and lifecycle to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 90 days." This is the most complete CloudTrail framing in chapter 12 to date and addresses the Finding S2 / M1 pattern from prior recipes head-on.
53:- **Severity:** HIGH
56:- **Problem:** The encryption row correctly elevates per-data-class CMKs (a step beyond the 12.2 and 12.3 framing that the 12.4 expert review elevated as Finding H1), but the three-CMK partition (PHI, operational, model artifacts) is not granular enough for the data classes this recipe actually creates. The full data-class inventory for this pipeline includes: (a) HealthLake FHIR datastore (PHI in the strongest sense; FHIR Encounter resources with patient identifiers, locations, and admission timelines), (b) raw ADT feeds in S3 (PHI), (c) OR-schedule feeds in S3 (PHI-by-association; surgical case schedules with patient identifiers and procedure types), (d) transfer-queue feeds in S3 (PHI-by-association; transfer requests with patient identifiers and accepting-physician assignments), (e) ED-board feeds in S3 (PHI; chief complaints, ED census, hold lists), (f) harmonized inference-features in S3 (PHI; per-patient feature vectors keyed by encounter_id and patient_id), (g) inflow samples in S3 (PHI-by-association; sample trajectories tied to per-cycle snapshots), (h) outflow samples in S3 (PHI-by-association; per-patient discharge-time draws), (i) forecast outputs in S3 (PHI-by-association at the forecast-cycle level even though aggregate at the unit level), (j) Monte Carlo trajectory archives in S3 (PHI-by-association), (k) inflow model artifacts (no PHI but high integrity-and-availability concern; a tampered inflow model produces wrong staffing decisions), (l) outflow / survival model artifacts (no PHI but high integrity concern), (m) unit-assignment model artifacts (no PHI), (n) DynamoDB serving table (PHI-by-association at the unit-hour level; the surfaced forecast and the explanation_text identify cohorts of patients), (o) Bedrock prompt-and-completion logs if narrative summaries are enabled (PHI-by-association; the prompts include per-patient counts and clinical states), (p) CloudWatch logs (may contain payload fragments and feature values from Step Functions and Lambda execution traces). A reader implementing the three-CMK partition gets the high-level shape right but mixes PHI and PHI-by-association data classes under a single CMK and grants overbroad cross-class access.
64:- **Severity:** MEDIUM
92:- **"Why This Isn't Production-Ready" correctly elevates ten structural gaps.** ADT timestamp reconciliation, discharge order timing model, capacity constraints and overflow logic, service-line and DRG drift, multi-hospital health-system rollouts, operational integration as the hard part, feedback capture and continuous calibration, human-in-the-loop for surge planning, privacy considerations for narrative summaries, regulatory framing (operational versus clinical decision support), idempotency and rerun safety. Each is operationally accurate and would be a HIGH or MEDIUM finding if not surfaced; the recipe correctly elevates them as known scope-cuts.
97:- **Severity:** HIGH
100:- **Problem:** The recipe's prose claims "explicit retries" and the diagram includes an "SNS DLQ" notation, but the architecture text and pseudocode do not specify retry counts, backoff, DLQ routing, per-step failure-tolerance, or stale-forecast signaling for missed cycles. A Step Functions pipeline with five serial stages (state snapshot -> inflow models -> outflow model -> Monte Carlo composition -> DynamoDB write) running every 15-60 minutes has five independent failure points each cycle. Without explicit retry policy and DLQ routing, the failure modes are: (a) HealthLake search fails on a transient infrastructure issue or hits a quota and the snapshot step aborts; the inference cycle is lost and the bed huddle dashboard reads stale data; (b) any of three SageMaker endpoints returns a 5xx on a transient issue and the cycle is lost; (c) the Monte Carlo Lambda hits the 15-minute timeout on a large hospital with finer time grids and the entire cycle is lost; (d) the DynamoDB BatchWriteItem fails on a partial-success-then-throttle scenario and a subset of unit forecasts are written while others are not, leaving the dashboard with mixed staleness across units (an especially bad failure mode because a transfer-center decision based on a partial forecast can route a transfer-in to a unit whose forecast did not refresh); (e) the optional Bedrock narrative-summary call fails and the structured forecast is written but the narrative is missing, producing inconsistent dashboard rendering. This finding mirrors Finding A1 in the 12.3 expert review and Finding H2 in the 12.4 expert review and is the chapter-wide consolidation pattern.
113:- **Severity:** HIGH
126:- **Severity:** HIGH
139:- **Severity:** MEDIUM
